'''Erondu–Cymet syndrome''' is a syndrome caused by a [[chromosomal translocation|translocation]] on the [[Chromosome 21 (human)|21st chromosome]].<ref name=ecs>{{Cite journal| pmid = 17898432| date = Winter 2006| last1 = Erondu  | volume = 32 | first1 = U. A.| issue = 4| last2 = Cymet | first2 = T. C.| title = Chromosome 21 abnormalities a review and report of a case of erondu-cymet syndrome| pages = 254–260| journal = Comprehensive Therapy| doi = 10.1007/BF02698072}}</ref>  The genetic [[karyotype]] for people with this condition is 46, XY, inv(21)(q11.2q22.1). Findings in these patients include [[hypotension]], [[hypoxemia]], [[seizure]]s, and impairment of [[cognition|cognitive ability]].<ref name=ecs/> Patients with this condition may have persistent left [[superior vena cava]] that drains into the [[left atrium]], as well as pulmonary [[arteriovenous malformations]]. Erondu–Cymet syndrome was discovered in 2006 by Ugochi Erondu and [[Tyler Cymet]].<ref name=ecs/>

