{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Hapnes Boman Skeie syndrome | synonyms = | image = Autosomal dominant - en.svg | image_size = 150px | alt = | caption = This condition is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner | pronounce = | field = | geneReviewsID = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }}
'''Hapnes Boman Skeie syndrome''' is a rare genetic disorder first described by Sveln Hapnes et al. in 1980. It is characterized by [[subcutaneous tissue|subcutaneous]] [[angiolipoma]]s around the wrists, knees, and ankles.<ref name="clingen">{{cite journal| last1=Hapnes| first1=Sveln A.| last2=Boman| first2=Helge| last3=Seele| first3=Sverre O.| journal=Clinical Genetics| volume=17| issue=3|date=March 1980| title=Familial angiolipomatosis| pages=202–208|doi=10.1111/j.1399-0004.1980.tb00133.x }}</ref> It is also known as "anomalous insertion of extensor tendons of fingers",<ref>{{cite web| publisher=Genetic & Rare Diseases Information Center| accessdate=2012-10-31| title= Tendons, extensor, of fingers, anomalous insertion of| url=http://rarediseases.info.nih.gov/GARD/Condition/2597/Tendons_extensor_of_fingers_anomalous_insertion_of.aspx}}</ref> a name derived from the condition that the tendons of the fingers are attached in such a way that the fingers cannot open or close normally. Though the tumors extend deeply into the muscle tissue, joints, and tendons, the tumors did not invade these structures.<ref name="clingen"/>
