{{update|date=October 2017}}
'''Strike 4 Repeal''' was an [[abortion rights]] protest in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] on [[International Women's Day]] 2017 (Wednesday 8 March 2017). It called for a repeal of the [[Eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|Eight Amendment]] of the [[Constitution of Ireland]], which bans [[abortion]] in nearly all cases, by recognising "the right to life of the unborn".<ref name="irishtimes-8-mar-2017">{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/thousands-march-against-eighth-amendment-in-dublin-1.3002375|title=Thousands march against Eighth Amendment in Dublin|date=8 March 2017|first1=Elaine|last1=Edwards|first2=Rachel|last2=Flaherty}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Independent|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/irish-women-abortion-ban-strike-international-day-2017-republic-ireland-consitutional-amendment-a7617461.html|title=Irish women go on strike over the abortion ban|date=8 March 2017|first=Katie|last=Forster}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/03/08/health/ireland-abortion-strike-womens-day/|publisher=CNN|title=#Strike4Repeal: Ireland protests abortion ban on International Women's Day |date=9 March 2017|first=Kara|last=Fox}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sligo Champion|url=http://www.independent.ie/regionals/sligochampion/news/pro-choice-activists-call-a-local-strike-for-repeal-35486698.html|title=Pro choice activists call a local strike for repeal|date=4 March 2017}}</ref><ref name="irishtimes.com">{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/strike4repeal-protests-in-quotes-and-pictures-1.3002504|title=Strike4Repeal protests: in quotes and pictures|date=8 March 2017}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|title=AJ+ - In Ireland, it&#039;s illegal for women to get an...|url=https://www.facebook.com/ajplusenglish/videos/916193148522193/|publisher=Al Jazerra+|date=9 March 2017}}</ref>
The protest was organised by Strike 4 Repeal, an ad-hoc, non-affiliated group of activists, academics, artists and trade unionists organising for abortion rights in Ireland. The main march was in [[Dublin]], with 10,000 people on [[O'Connell Bridge]],<ref name="irishtimes-8-mar-2017" /><ref>{{cite newspaper|newspaper=Irish Central|url=http://www.irishcentral.com/news/politics/women-across-ireland-are-on-strike-for-international-women-s-day-here-s-why|title=Thousands of Strike 4 Repeal protests takeover O'Connell Bridge (VIDEO)|date=8 March 2017|first=Katie|last=Hickey}}</ref> and later many outside other government buildings. Despite the name "strike" some people took paid holidays that day. There were also protests in Galway, Limerick, Cork & other cities & towns around Ireland.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Sun|url=https://www.thesun.ie/news/683815/powerful-scenes-as-throngs-of-women-gather-on-irish-streets-to-strike-4-repeal-on-international-womens-day/|title=Powerful scenes as thousands of women gather on Irish streets to Strike 4 Repeal on International Women’s Day|first=Emma|last=O'Rourke|date=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://traleetoday.ie/kerry-choice-holds-strike-4-repeal-square/|newspaper=Tralee Today|date=10 March 2017|title=Kerry For Choice Holds ‘Strike 4 Repeal’ In The Square|first=Dermot|last=Crean}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Cork Independent|url=http://www.corkindependent.com/news/topics/articles/2017/03/08/4136192-strike-4-repeal-actions-take-place-later-today/|title=Strike 4 Repeal actions take place later today|date=8 March 2017|first=Niamh Aine|last=Ryan}}</ref> A protest was also held outside the Irish Embassy in [[London]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/abroad/generation-emigration/we-re-striking-for-repeal-in-london-in-solidarity-with-our-sisters-in-ireland-1.3002461|title=‘We’re striking for Repeal in London in solidarity with our sisters in Ireland’|location=London|first=Claire|last=McGowran}}</ref>
It was inspired by a similar [[Abortion in Poland#Black Protest|Black Protest]] in [[Poland]] several months earlier, which itself was inspired by the [[1975 Icelandic women's strike]].<ref name="irishtimes-8-mar-2017" /><ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-39183423?ocid=socialflow_twitter|title=Abortion in Ireland: The fight for choice|date=8 March 2017|first=Joel|last=Gunter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abortionrightscampaign.ie/2017/01/30/strike-4-repeal/|publisher=[[Abortion Rights Campaign]]|date=20 January 2017|title=Strike 4 Repeal}}</ref>
The march, and repeal movement, was criticised by some [[anti-abortion]] writers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/why-the-repeal-the-eighth-march-will-backfire-1.3001535|title=Why the Repeal the Eighth march will backfire|date=8 March 2017|newspaper=The Irish Times|first=Larissa|last=Nolan}}</ref>
Some participants thought the coverage of the event on [[Raidió Teilifís Éireann|RTÉ]], Ireland's national broadcaster, was insufficient, and organised a follow-up picket of RTÉ studios. <ref>{{cite news|newspaper=University Observer|url=http://www.universityobserver.ie/news/ucd-students-lead-rte-repeal-protest/|title=UCD Students Lead RTÉ Repeal Protest|date=13 March 2017|first=Roisin|last=Guyett-Nicholson}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shemazing.net/repeal-protesters-set-to-picket-rte-to-demand-recognition-for-strike/|title=Repeal protesters set to picket RTÉ to demand recognition for strike|first=Sarah|last=Magliocco|date=10 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/student-hub/ucd-students-organise-rt%C3%A9-repeal-protest-1.3009256|title=UCD students organise RTÉ 'Repeal protest'|date=13 March 2016|first=Roisin|last=Guyett-Nicholson}}</ref>
In 2016, the Irish government convened a [[Citizens' Assembly (Ireland)|Citizens' Assembly]] to make non-binding recommendations on this constitutional ban on abortion, and it was still deliberating on the day of the protest. {{As of|2017|03}} the Assembly hasn't finished its work. The protest also took place as details about the [[Bon Secours Mother and Baby Home]] in [[Tuam]] were being revealed, with some posters referencing those events.<ref name="irishtimes.com"/>
==See also== * [[Abortion in the Republic of Ireland]] * [[Eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland]], the constitutional amendment the campaigners want to repeal * [[Citizens' Assembly (Ireland)]], which is discussing the Eighth Amendment at the same time
